text:
• If you run into the error something like "'fatal: repository not found'" error in git", check the following:
    ◦ Did you move back to your project/repo directory from the .ssh directory? You must be in your version-controlled folder to sync it to GitHub.
    ◦ Did you set the url for GitHub correctly? You can try resetting it with *git remote set-url origin _your-repo-url-on-github_.*
• Did you follow the advice on the phases above and still receive the same error(s)? You can try adding your repo again and working from there. Here are the steps (note the period after "add" in the second step).
        ▪︎ *git remote rm origin* 
        ▪︎ *git add .*
        ▪︎ *git branch -M main* 
        ▪︎ *git commit -m "First commit"*
        ▪︎ *git remote add origin _your-repo-url-on-github_*
        ▪︎ *git push -u origin main*

elements.text: If you run into the error something like "'fatal: repository not found'" error in git", check the following:
Did you move back to your project/repo directory from the .ssh directory? You must be in your version-controlled folder to sync it to GitHub.
Did you set the url for GitHub correctly? You can try resetting it with
git remote set-url origin
your-repo-url-on-github

Did you follow the advice on the phases above and still receive the same error(s)? You can try adding your repo again and working from there. Here are the steps (note the period after "add" in the second step).
git remote rm origin
git add .
git branch -M main
git commit -m "First commit"
git remote add origin
your-repo-url-on-github
git push -u origin main
